visuals.title: Collision 03
visuals.description:
Exploring 2-dimensional elastic collisions between equal circular bodies. The red and blue data to the right represents vector magnitude of each body; the purple is the magnitude of the sum vector.

At first glance, it would appear that the law of conserved kinetic energy is getting violated, but as far as I understand, it's just the bouncing off the unmoving walls that make it appear that way. Maybe someone with a better understanding of the physics and math involved could elaborate.

visuals.description:
A text-painter, with color coming (primarily) from 4 possible images.
Try painting a grid, reducing the size, and painting again!

UP/DOWN - change text size
LEFT/RIGHT - change amount of "jitter" (random offset for painting)
a - toggle AutoPaint (on/off)
1,2,3,4 - change color-source image
          stored as square "001.jpg" etc, in the data folder
g - paint a grid of text covering entire screen (may take a while in .js)
m/M - change paint Mode (the default mode takes color from images)
s - save
x - change black/white mode
c - clear screen

visuals.description:
Another drawing machine, creates an one line drawing based on a given image.

Has two modes: Mode one always looks for the nearest neighbor and connects this two points. Mode two looks up for the 7 nearest neighbors and chooses one of these randomly. Last one makes it look more like a natural drawing.

Controls: 
Mouse click == start over
1-9 == particle number (+start)
I == show / hide image
N == connection mode 
M == straight or curly lines

(Photo is takes by me. It's my small Delorean which decorates my desk)

visuals.title: Prime Palindomes
visuals.description:
Label every integer as prime (P) or composite (C). The integers will contain palindromic subsequences of these labels. For example, the sequence from 4 to 20 is CPCPCCCPCPCCCPCPC, a palindrome (and the longest one possible that's centred on 12).

This sketch shows a number line. Every semicircular arc bounds one of the palindromes described above. Only palindromes centred on even numbers are shown. They are coloured according to the distance from the centre of the palindrome to the nearest prime (so, for example, even numbers between twin primes are reddest).
visuals.instructions: Drag the number line with the mouse, or use the arrow keys to explore out to 100000.
